First, let's understand the problem setup. A Wigner matrix is an n×n random matrix where the diagonal entries have a probability distribution ν and the off-diagonal entries have a probability distribution μ. The matrix is symmetric, meaning the entries above and below the diagonal are equal. The scaled Wigner matrix is obtained by dividing each entry by √n.

The theorem `wignerMatrixMomentOddExpectation` states that for an odd k, the expectation of the trace of the kth power of the scaled Wigner matrix tends to 0 as n tends to infinity. 

The key insight is that for odd k, the expectation of the trace of the kth power of a symmetric matrix is the sum of the expectations of the kth powers of the individual entries. Because the matrix is symmetric, the off-diagonal entries are pairs of equal entries. For odd k, the expectation of the kth power of an off-diagonal entry (which has distribution μ) will be the same as the expectation of the kth power of the corresponding diagonal entry (which has distribution ν). But since k is odd, we can show that the expectation of the kth power of the off-diagonal entry will be zero in the limit as n tends to infinity, making the entire trace expectation zero.

