For odd k, the expectation of the trace of the kth power of a symmetric matrix is known to be related to the sum of the eigenvalues raised to the kth power. For a Wigner matrix, the eigenvalues are known to satisfy certain properties, and their sum is related to the trace of the matrix.

The trace of the matrix itself is the sum of the diagonal entries. For the kth power, the trace of the kth power is the sum of the eigenvalues raised to the kth power.

For a Wigner matrix, the eigenvalues are known to be approximately ±√(2 log n) for large n, but their exact distribution is complex. However, for odd k, the expectation of the trace of the kth power of the matrix is known to be zero in the limit as n tends to infinity.

