# Solving the Wigner Matrix Problem in Lean 4

We need to prove that for any odd k, the expectation of the scaled trace of the kth power of an n × n Wigner matrix tends to 0 as n approaches infinity.

First, let's understand the problem setup. A Wigner matrix is a symmetric matrix where the diagonal entries have law ν and the off-diagonal entries have law μ, and are independent. The matrix is then scaled by 1/√n to form the Wigner matrix map.

We need to show that the expectation of the trace of the kth power of this scaled matrix tends to 0 when n tends to infinity, for k odd.

To approach this, we need to compute the expectation of the trace of the kth power of the matrix and show it tends to 0.

The trace of the kth power of the matrix is the sum of the kth powers of the matrix entries on the diagonal.

For the Wigner matrix, the diagonal entries have law ν and the off-diagonal entries have law μ.

When k is odd, the expectation of the kth power of the off-diagonal entries (which have law μ) will be odd multiples of the mean of μ. If μ is symmetric, then the expectation of the kth power for k odd will be 0.

Similarly, the diagonal entries have law ν. If ν is symmetric, then the expectation of the kth power for k odd will be 0.

Therefore, all entries of the matrix raised to the kth power (for k odd) will have expectation 0.

Therefore, the trace will also have expectation 0.

In the proof, we need to formalize this argument.

